<font color="#ec14bd">www.addic7ed.com</font>

01:21.363 --> 01:24.642
Hi. Um, I need to talk to
somebody about reserving a park.

01:24.660 --> 01:26.244
Oh, we have a new policy.

01:26.279 --> 01:28.346
Parks can only be reserved
for witch covens

01:28.381 --> 01:30.098
or slip-and-slide
competitions.

01:30.149 --> 01:31.132
Which one are you?

01:31.167 --> 01:32.367
Uh,
slip-and-slide competition.

01:32.401 --> 01:34.118
- Seriously?
- No.

01:34.136 --> 01:36.271
Why would you even compete
in something like that?

01:36.305 --> 01:37.656
It doesn't matter.

01:37.690 --> 01:39.574
Um, I called earlier about
the free vaccinations thing.

01:39.625 --> 01:42.594
We're hoping to set up
a mobile hospital

01:42.628 --> 01:44.629
in one of your parks.

01:44.664 --> 01:46.424
I'm sorry, is there
something wrong with him?

01:47.466 --> 01:49.784
Tom, this witch wants to
reserve a park

01:49.819 --> 01:50.769
for her satanic ritual.

01:50.803 --> 01:52.437
Can you help her?

01:52.455 --> 01:53.855
[British accent]
Right. Smashing.

01:53.889 --> 01:55.974
Uh, yes, I'm Thomas Haverford.

01:56.008 --> 01:58.143
I sort of run
the whole department.

01:58.177 --> 01:59.794
Um, what was the name, then?

01:59.829 --> 02:00.962
Uh, Nadia Statsky.

02:00.997 --> 02:02.213
I'm from Doctors
Without Borders.

02:02.247 --> 02:04.933
Brilliant.
The old "D"s without "B"s.

02:04.984 --> 02:07.836
Uh, we can definitely help.

02:07.870 --> 02:09.304
Yeah, Tom's your guy.

02:09.338 --> 02:11.306
He actually used to run
the Parks Department

02:11.357 --> 02:12.991
in his home country of Russia.

02:13.025 --> 02:16.344
[Laughs] This one is mental.

02:16.379 --> 02:18.313
She's joking, obviously.

02:18.364 --> 02:19.331
How could I be from Russia?

02:19.365 --> 02:21.583
Not with this spot-on
British accent.

02:21.617 --> 02:23.568
We can definitely
get you sorted.

02:23.602 --> 02:25.186
Right this way.

02:25.237 --> 02:26.204
Okay.

02:28.540 --> 02:31.860
Whoa. I am pretty sure you
shouldn't have a weapon at work.

02:31.894 --> 02:34.546
Literally everything
is a weapon, son.

02:34.580 --> 02:36.881
That folder, in my hands,
is far deadlier

02:36.899 --> 02:38.183
than this bow in yours.

02:38.217 --> 02:40.402
Oh, that's...
probably true.

02:40.453 --> 02:42.454
So, Leslie and I just
finished putting together

02:42.488 --> 02:44.306
our will, and she wants you
to be the witness.

02:44.340 --> 02:45.390
You mind signing it?

02:45.424 --> 02:46.691
That's your will?

02:46.725 --> 02:48.326
You need that many pages
to say,

02:48.360 --> 02:49.594
"Give my stuff to my wife"?

02:49.628 --> 02:51.396
It's a complicated
legal document.

02:51.430 --> 02:52.731
It doesn't have to be.

02:52.765 --> 02:56.301
I've had the same will
since I was eight years old.

02:57.853 --> 03:00.104
"Upon my death,
all of my belongings

03:00.122 --> 03:02.123
"shall transfer
to the man or animal

03:02.158 --> 03:03.842
who has killed me."

03:03.876 --> 03:05.527
What are these weird symbols?

03:05.561 --> 03:08.196
The man who kills me will know.

03:08.247 --> 03:10.298
Okay, you should really
have a will

03:10.333 --> 03:12.350
that's more than
one sentence long.

03:12.384 --> 03:14.069
You have a wife and kids now.

03:14.120 --> 03:15.253
I could introduce you
to our lawyer.

03:15.287 --> 03:17.455
The three most useless
jobs in the world

03:17.473 --> 03:20.442
are, in order, lawyer,
congressman, and doctor.

03:20.493 --> 03:21.576
Pass.

03:21.610 --> 03:23.178
Ron, that document is nothing.

03:23.212 --> 03:24.429
It's not even notarized.

03:24.463 --> 03:25.730
You know, if you die

03:25.764 --> 03:27.065
and you don't have a real will,

03:27.099 --> 03:29.200
most of what you own
will go to the government.

03:29.218 --> 03:32.771
Where is this lawyer
you speak of?

03:32.805 --> 03:35.990
I'm pleased to
formally submit Bill 68-J,

03:36.042 --> 03:38.843
which funds a new bike path
in Ramsett Park.

03:38.878 --> 03:41.062
- Motion to table this bill.
- Second.

03:41.097 --> 03:43.581
- I also submit Bill 68-R.
- Motion to table.

03:43.616 --> 03:44.699
Second.

03:44.750 --> 03:46.284
You guys want to delay
all my bills? Fine.

03:46.318 --> 03:47.285
I'm just gonna
keep my head down

03:47.303 --> 03:48.670
and continue to get work done.

03:48.721 --> 03:50.721
All right, well, uh,
motion to end this session early

03:50.740 --> 03:52.056
so nothing can get done.

03:52.074 --> 03:53.057
Second.

03:53.075 --> 03:54.542
Gahhh, you guys are the worst!

03:54.593 --> 03:55.677
Sorry, Knope.

03:55.711 --> 03:56.978
We're just looking for
any possible way

03:57.012 --> 03:58.763
to get you recalled
because we don't like you.

03:58.797 --> 04:01.116
- It's nothing personal.
- It absolutely <i>is</i> personal.

04:01.167 --> 04:02.917
That is the definition
of "personal."

04:02.952 --> 04:04.836
"The definition of personal."
[Recording of passing gas]

04:04.870 --> 04:06.604
[Laughter]

04:06.638 --> 04:09.240
Excuse me, we have an issue.

04:09.274 --> 04:11.893
A tweet has been tweeted from
the Parks and Rec Twitter,

04:11.927 --> 04:14.095
and I'm afraid it is quite
sexually graphic.

04:14.146 --> 04:15.313
[Groans]

04:15.347 --> 04:16.613
It's probably just
some bored teenager

04:16.648 --> 04:17.665
who hacked the account.

04:17.716 --> 04:20.935
Whoever it is,
it's quite serious.

04:20.986 --> 04:22.787
I don't want you to get
recalled Knope,

04:22.822 --> 04:24.622
but damn, these people know how
to pick a neck massager.

04:24.656 --> 04:26.424
And before you get on my case
about those stickers,

04:26.459 --> 04:27.559
I already did 'em.

04:27.593 --> 04:29.644
Donna, there is
trouble a-brewin'.

04:29.695 --> 04:31.796
We think that you
may have accidentally

04:31.831 --> 04:33.715
tweeted from
the Parks and Rec account

04:33.749 --> 04:35.250
rather than your own
personal account.

04:35.284 --> 04:36.768
Uh-oh.
What'd it say?

04:36.802 --> 04:37.769
"See you tonight.

04:37.803 --> 04:39.204
"Hope you like tongue baths,

04:39.238 --> 04:41.372
you big, nasty fireman."

04:41.407 --> 04:43.291
Then there's a picture
of a pair of lips

04:43.342 --> 04:44.759
and then a picture
of an eggplant.

04:44.810 --> 04:47.112
I'm both confused, and if
we're being totally honest,

04:47.146 --> 04:48.079
a little aroused.

04:48.114 --> 04:49.531
Ew.

04:49.582 --> 04:51.082
Not to give you too much of
a peek into my personal life,

04:51.116 --> 04:53.084
but this could have been
way worse.

04:53.118 --> 04:54.769
What's important is,
we deleted the tweet,

04:54.804 --> 04:56.087
and nobody is gonna know
it's you,

04:56.105 --> 04:58.106
but Donna, you know, be more
careful in the future.

04:58.157 --> 05:00.291
This almost blew up in my face.

05:00.326 --> 05:02.744
[News theme music]

05:02.778 --> 05:05.230
I'm here live,
at a press conference,

05:05.264 --> 05:06.664
where Councilman Jeremy Jamm

05:06.699 --> 05:08.750
will discuss
a government scandal

05:08.784 --> 05:10.685
we are calling
"Twitter Watergate"

05:10.719 --> 05:13.421
until we can find
a snappier name for it.

05:13.456 --> 05:16.241
Tongue baths?
Eggplants?

05:16.275 --> 05:17.559
Firemen?

05:17.593 --> 05:20.328
Those men are heroes
who deserve respect!

05:20.362 --> 05:22.347
9/11!
[Cheers and applause]

05:22.381 --> 05:24.782
This is how Leslie Knope
runs her Parks Department?

05:24.817 --> 05:27.502
We are going to hold
hearing after hearing,

05:27.536 --> 05:28.803
until we are satisfied.

05:28.838 --> 05:31.473
This will be blown
<i>way</i> out of proportion!

05:31.524 --> 05:33.257
You have my word on it!
[Cheers and applause]

05:33.275 --> 05:34.425
[TV turns off]
Ugh.

05:34.443 --> 05:36.427
Ooh, this is bad.
I'm gonna get fired.

05:36.445 --> 05:38.279
No one is getting fired, okay?

05:38.330 --> 05:41.065
Jamm is trying to use this
to hurt me in the recall.

05:41.083 --> 05:42.500
He's trying to take me down,

05:42.535 --> 05:44.786
and he's willing to attack
my friends in the process?

05:44.837 --> 05:46.955
- No. No way. Not on my watch.
- Not on her watch.

05:47.006 --> 05:48.423
He is not gonna
Sully your name.

05:48.457 --> 05:49.457
No sullying allowed!

05:49.508 --> 05:50.558
Don't worry about it, Donna.

05:50.593 --> 05:52.093
We're gonna nip this
in the bud.

05:52.127 --> 05:53.294
Guard your buds, 'cause
they're about to get nipped!

05:53.345 --> 05:54.879
- Okay.
- Okay.

05:56.644 --> 05:59.842
So, why does Doctors
Without Borders

05:59.962 --> 06:00.883
want to come to Pawnee?

06:01.065 --> 06:03.553
Pawnee is like
a petri dish of weird diseases.

06:03.587 --> 06:05.772
Did you know you have a higher
rate of the West Nile virus

06:05.806 --> 06:07.206
than the actual Western Nile?

06:07.241 --> 06:10.376
Sorry, West Nile,
looks like Pawnee wins again.

06:10.394 --> 06:13.997
What else have you beaten
the Western Nile in?

06:14.048 --> 06:16.199
Cricket.
Uh...

06:16.233 --> 06:19.652
just fill out these forms,
and we will be all set

06:19.686 --> 06:22.472
like two biscuits inside a tin.

06:24.891 --> 06:28.294
So, you've gone insane.
That's fun.

06:28.312 --> 06:29.262
I just panicked.

06:29.296 --> 06:30.336
She's so out of my league,

06:30.347 --> 06:31.281
my brain just made me
talk that way

06:31.315 --> 06:32.248
so I'd seem cooler.

06:32.283 --> 06:33.249
What should I do?

06:33.284 --> 06:34.634
Nothing!
This is amazing.

06:34.668 --> 06:37.070
- April.
- Fine.

06:37.104 --> 06:38.137
If you want to have
a chance with her,

06:38.172 --> 06:39.973
obviously, you have to stop.

06:40.007 --> 06:41.224
It's either that,
or you talk like that

06:41.275 --> 06:42.442
for the rest of your life.

06:42.476 --> 06:45.461
You think she'd marry me?

06:45.512 --> 06:47.563
All right, just let me
do the talking here, okay?

06:47.598 --> 06:49.332
I mean, he's a lawyer,
I'm an accountant.

06:49.366 --> 06:50.783
We speak the same language.

06:50.818 --> 06:53.987
I mean, obviously, accountants
are a little more bad boy,

06:54.021 --> 06:56.422
but, uh,
there's a respect there.

06:56.457 --> 06:58.458
- When will this be over?
- Hey, Trevor.

06:58.492 --> 07:00.643
I've been talking to Ron
about estate planning,

07:00.694 --> 07:05.365
and he is here to do
some "Good Will Hunting."

07:05.399 --> 07:07.867
Because he has to
draw up a new will, so--

07:07.901 --> 07:09.462
Yes, I understood,
Mr. Wyatt. Thank you.

07:09.486 --> 07:11.471
As I've said before,
I just don't like puns.

07:11.505 --> 07:14.140
Oh, well, my accountant
friends seem to enjoy 'em.

07:14.158 --> 07:17.410
Mr. Swanson, let's begin
by filling out this form,

07:17.444 --> 07:18.411
listing your assets
and liabilities.

07:18.429 --> 07:20.013
Nice try.

07:20.047 --> 07:22.165
I'm not telling you
how much money I have,

07:22.199 --> 07:24.467
where it's hidden,
or which precious metals

07:24.501 --> 07:27.954
and/or gemstones it may
or may not take the form of.

07:27.988 --> 07:29.122
If you don't give me
the information I need,

07:29.156 --> 07:30.156
there's nothing I can do.

07:30.190 --> 07:31.391
Oh, come on, Trevor.

07:31.425 --> 07:34.610
Where there's a "Will,"
there's a way.

07:34.662 --> 07:36.879
I'm gonna say this
one last time, Wyatt.

07:36.914 --> 07:38.514
Check the accountant crap
at the door.

07:38.549 --> 07:40.316
Yes, sir, I will.

07:40.367 --> 07:41.868
Unintentional.

07:41.902 --> 07:43.886
All right, let's begin.

07:43.937 --> 07:45.972
These hearings have two goals.

07:46.006 --> 07:49.125
One, to find out exactly
how this offensive tweet

07:49.176 --> 07:50.343
came to be sent.

07:50.377 --> 07:52.145
And two,
to turn this whole thing

07:52.179 --> 07:53.379
into a media circus.

07:53.397 --> 07:54.947
Ms. Knope, do you have
a statement?

07:54.981 --> 07:56.342
Well, it's actually
quite simple.

07:56.367 --> 07:59.886
Uh, a Parks and Rec
employee forgot to log out

07:59.920 --> 08:01.360
of the Parks and Rec
Twitter account,

08:01.905 --> 08:05.591
they posted a personal, of the Parks 
and Rec private message by accident,

08:05.626 --> 08:07.310
and, uh, that person
is very sorry,

08:07.344 --> 08:08.444
and it won't happen again.

08:08.495 --> 08:10.029
Stop stonewalling

08:10.064 --> 08:11.414
and tell us what happened here!

08:11.465 --> 08:13.049
I just told you what happened.

08:13.100 --> 08:15.151
It was an unfortunate mistake.

08:15.185 --> 08:17.553
Okay, sadly,
due to your "intracksidence"--

08:17.588 --> 08:18.588
Not a word.

08:18.639 --> 08:20.139
We may never find out
what happened.

08:20.174 --> 08:23.275
When this sick, depraved tweet
first came to light,

08:23.293 --> 08:26.512
you said, "The account
was probably hacked

08:26.547 --> 08:28.564
by some bored teenager."

08:28.615 --> 08:31.784
Now you're saying
it's an unfortunate mistake.

08:31.818 --> 08:33.251
Why do you keep
flip-flopping?

08:33.285 --> 08:35.722
Well, because I learned
new information.

08:35.756 --> 08:37.924
When I was four,
I thought that chocolate milk

08:37.957 --> 08:39.542
came from brown cows,

08:39.592 --> 08:42.445
and then I flip-flopped
when I found out

08:42.479 --> 08:44.914
that there was something
called chocolate syrup.

08:44.948 --> 08:46.549
I don't think I'm
out of line when I say

08:46.583 --> 08:50.403
that this scandal makes Benghazi
look like whitewater!

08:50.437 --> 08:51.738
It's utterly meaningless.

08:51.772 --> 08:54.340
I think we need to hear
from the unnamed employee

08:54.374 --> 08:55.425
behind the tweet.

08:55.476 --> 08:57.744
- Perhaps he or she--
- Or them.

08:57.778 --> 09:00.079
It could be a bunch
of hot ladies.

09:00.113 --> 09:01.431
Yes, perhaps "them"

09:01.465 --> 09:04.834
can finally give us
the answers we need.

09:04.868 --> 09:07.720
What, what, what?
There she is.

09:07.754 --> 09:09.305
Nadia, I didn't know
what you wanted,

09:09.356 --> 09:11.190
so I got you a cappuccino,
a latte,

09:11.208 --> 09:14.594
four bags of coffee beans,
and a mini espresso machine.

09:14.628 --> 09:16.729
What happened to your accent?

09:16.763 --> 09:20.700
Oh, yeah.
It's gone. Huh.

09:20.734 --> 09:23.069
You know, I had a cold
recently.

09:23.103 --> 09:25.137
I think that may have
affected my voice,

09:25.155 --> 09:27.757
like, in certain British ways.

09:27.791 --> 09:29.609
Well, that's all there is
to that story,

09:29.643 --> 09:31.010
so no need for
any more questions.

09:31.028 --> 09:32.111
You have a cold?

09:32.146 --> 09:34.080
Can I feel your glands?

09:34.114 --> 09:35.998
Sure.

09:36.049 --> 09:38.676
Wow, you are wearing a lot of
moisturizer on your throat.

09:38.796 --> 09:40.736
Best way to prevent crow's neck.

09:40.788 --> 09:42.588
Is this glitter?

09:42.623 --> 09:44.089
So, those are the forms.

09:44.108 --> 09:45.441
You filled 'em out.
Great.

09:45.492 --> 09:47.376
April's gonna file these.

09:47.411 --> 09:50.179
Hey, when is the thing
you're doing in the park?

09:50.230 --> 09:53.732
I'd love to come by and maybe
help administer vaccines?

09:53.750 --> 09:55.968
Oh. Are you a doctor,
somehow?

09:56.003 --> 09:58.571
No.

09:58.605 --> 10:00.907
No follow-up to that?
Okay, great.

10:00.941 --> 10:03.426
Um, well, I'm not actually gonna
be attending the event,

10:03.460 --> 10:04.977
so if you could
just give me the permit,

10:05.012 --> 10:06.262
so that I can go home
to Indianapolis

10:06.296 --> 10:09.882
and never come back here?

10:09.917 --> 10:14.070
I am in love with Nadia
Whatever-her-last-name-is,

10:14.121 --> 10:15.454
and I'm gonna keep her here,

10:15.489 --> 10:17.089
using the most powerful
weapon I have--

10:17.123 --> 10:19.642
bureaucratic incompetence.

10:19.693 --> 10:24.547
Oh, no. You filled out
Form 3208.

10:24.581 --> 10:27.216
You were supposed to
fill out Form 3248.

10:27.251 --> 10:28.901
Oh, God.

10:28.935 --> 10:30.736
This is to lease a hangar
at the airport.

10:30.754 --> 10:33.055
I know. It's so crazy,
it almost sounds made up.

10:33.090 --> 10:34.440
Bureaucracy, right?

10:34.474 --> 10:37.460
What are you gonna do?
Huh. Weird.

10:37.494 --> 10:40.596
Someone left out a blender,
fresh fruits, and rum?

10:40.631 --> 10:42.648
I guess we gotta, like,
make Daiquiris now.

10:42.683 --> 10:45.034
I like to have music on
while I work, you know?

10:45.068 --> 10:47.553
[Music playing]

10:47.588 --> 10:50.223
What <i>is</i> this place?

10:50.257 --> 10:52.041
[Gavel bangs]

10:52.075 --> 10:54.377
Ms. Meagle,
let me first say

10:54.428 --> 10:56.812
that I am a big fan
of your writing.

10:56.847 --> 10:58.698
Thank you.

10:58.732 --> 11:00.132
It's good stuff.

11:00.167 --> 11:02.635
Really good stuff.

11:02.669 --> 11:04.937
Okay, does anyone else here
see a double standard?

11:04.972 --> 11:07.106
Councilman Dexhart
is currently being sued

11:07.140 --> 11:09.158
by two different women
for sexual harassment,

11:09.209 --> 11:12.111
one of whom was the judge
in the first woman's trial.

11:12.145 --> 11:13.763
She was talking dirty to me.

11:13.814 --> 11:14.897
She was reading the emails

11:14.948 --> 11:16.365
that you sent
to the first woman.

11:16.400 --> 11:17.950
Look, I obviously

11:17.984 --> 11:20.636
never meant to embarrass
the parks department.

11:20.687 --> 11:22.655
My personal account
is set to "private."

11:22.689 --> 11:24.957
Yeah, I don't even know
what she writes on there!

11:24.992 --> 11:27.376
Well, you may not know
what she's writing, but we do.

11:27.427 --> 11:30.863
In a shocking twist
to an already juicy story,

11:30.898 --> 11:33.466
we have obtained access
to Ms. Meagle's account,

11:33.500 --> 11:36.102
via a third party.

11:36.136 --> 11:37.904
Same hairdresser.

11:37.938 --> 11:41.407
Damn it, Typhoon!
Why'd you do this?

11:41.425 --> 11:42.808
Maybe if you had bothered

11:42.843 --> 11:46.395
to come to my <i>Great Gatsby</i>
<i>Brunch,</i> you'd know.

11:46.446 --> 11:47.997
I don't even need
an exact number.

11:48.031 --> 11:49.114
Just ballpark it.

11:49.132 --> 11:50.600
That's all I need
to get started.

11:50.634 --> 11:51.884
Or, I'm sure
the state government

11:51.902 --> 11:53.102
would love to use your money

11:53.153 --> 11:55.755
to hire more bureaucrats,
maybe build a library.

11:55.789 --> 11:58.958
Fine, a ballpark figure.

11:58.992 --> 12:00.610
Thank you.
God.

12:06.166 --> 12:07.633
Holy [bleep].

12:07.668 --> 12:09.151
Is this a joke?

12:09.186 --> 12:11.404
Another word for "jokes"
is "lies."

12:11.438 --> 12:14.173
I do not lie.
Therefore, I do not joke.

12:14.207 --> 12:16.225
Mr. Swanson,
an estate of this size

12:16.260 --> 12:17.360
means that your children

12:17.394 --> 12:19.028
would never have to work
a day in their lives.

12:19.079 --> 12:20.779
This is going to take
some time.

12:20.797 --> 12:22.765
Trusts need to be drawn,
tax shelters.

12:22.799 --> 12:24.083
That's enough.

12:24.101 --> 12:27.186
I do not need some drawn-out
legal expedition

12:27.204 --> 12:28.821
to tell me what I knew
when I was eight.

12:28.855 --> 12:30.389
Here's my original will.

12:30.424 --> 12:32.391
Do whatever lawyer nonsense
you have to

12:32.426 --> 12:33.392
to make it official,
and I will sign it.

12:33.426 --> 12:34.944
Good day.

12:34.978 --> 12:37.079
Wait.
What are all these symbols?

12:37.114 --> 12:38.364
[Laughs]

12:38.382 --> 12:41.550
I was right not to be
threatened by you.

12:41.601 --> 12:44.370
Okay, I would like to
enter into the record

12:44.404 --> 12:46.756
a selection
of Ms. Meagle's tweets.

12:46.790 --> 12:49.225
Uh-oh. Uh, can I request
a brief recess?

12:49.259 --> 12:51.176
It's okay, Donna. I'm not
gonna let them fire you.

12:51.194 --> 12:53.162
Yeah, it's not me
I'm worried about.

12:53.196 --> 12:55.280
Ms. Beavers,
if you please.

12:55.299 --> 12:57.633
Yesterday, 9:02 A.M.

12:57.684 --> 12:59.819
"Annoying-ass Leslie

12:59.853 --> 13:02.321
"has given me another
annoying-ass task.

13:02.339 --> 13:05.875
#stickers, #bitchboss."

13:05.909 --> 13:08.394
- [Laughs]
- September 25th.

13:08.428 --> 13:12.315
"Twitter poll: On a scale
of 98 to 100,

13:12.366 --> 13:14.650
"how annoying is Leslie Knope?

13:14.701 --> 13:17.753
"Cuz u know it ain't
less than 98.

13:17.788 --> 13:22.475
All my #trueblood fans
know what's up."

13:22.509 --> 13:27.179
Page after page of personal
attacks on Leslie Knope.

13:27.213 --> 13:30.049
Not only do you have no control
over your department,

13:30.067 --> 13:32.268
you don't even have the respect
of your employees.

13:32.319 --> 13:33.385
That's what you really
think of me?

13:33.403 --> 13:34.570
You think I'm annoying?

13:34.604 --> 13:37.123
Leslie, sometimes
you're kind of annoying.

13:37.157 --> 13:38.557
I mean, I thought
that was your thing.

13:38.575 --> 13:41.494
My thing? My thing
is not being annoying.

13:41.528 --> 13:44.413
My things are making
friendship bracelets

13:44.448 --> 13:46.365
and dancing like
nobody's watching,

13:46.399 --> 13:48.784
thinking up really cool
nicknames for my friends.

13:48.835 --> 13:51.620
You of all people should
know that, El Diablo!

13:51.671 --> 13:53.205
Look, the only reason
I'm even on Twitter

13:53.239 --> 13:54.623
is to blow off steam about work

13:54.674 --> 13:57.242
and tweet nasty stuff to dudes
with washboard abs.

13:57.260 --> 13:59.045
You really think I hate you,

13:59.079 --> 14:01.580
after all we've been through
the last ten years?

14:01.598 --> 14:03.549
I honestly don't know anymore.

14:03.583 --> 14:04.816
[Gavel bangs]

14:04.936 --> 14:07.386
Okay, I think we've done
a lot of good here today.

14:13.098 --> 14:15.467
Leslie, I am sorry, but I could not
postpone

14:15.587 --> 14:17.258
these pointless hearings
that Jamm is having.

14:17.276 --> 14:18.397
He is just determined.

14:18.496 --> 14:20.004
Well, thank you for trying.

14:20.124 --> 14:21.215
I have a question for you.

14:21.546 --> 14:22.629
Do you think I'm annoying?

14:22.680 --> 14:23.780
- No.
- Are you lying?

14:23.815 --> 14:25.616
- No.
- Are you trying to protect my feelings?

14:25.735 --> 14:26.337
No.

14:26.457 --> 14:27.434
Do you think I'm being
annoying right now?

14:27.554 --> 14:29.436
- Yes.
- So you <i>do</i> think I'm annoying.

14:29.470 --> 14:31.204
I think that you ask a lot

14:31.239 --> 14:32.472
of the people
that you work with,

14:32.507 --> 14:34.825
and I think that people do
what you ask

14:34.859 --> 14:36.109
because they love you.

14:36.160 --> 14:39.379
But, I also think that driving
people as hard as you do

14:39.430 --> 14:41.448
can ruffle some feathers.

14:41.482 --> 14:43.333
I think a lot of things.
I like thinking.

14:43.368 --> 14:44.368
And racquetball.

14:44.402 --> 14:45.469
Now who's annoying?

14:45.503 --> 14:46.837
I spent the last hour

14:46.871 --> 14:48.422
reading some of Donna's
old tweets,

14:48.456 --> 14:49.856
and it turns out
there are some more things

14:49.907 --> 14:50.907
that she said about you.

14:50.942 --> 14:52.659
"Message to the recall haters:

14:52.710 --> 14:54.411
"You can't keep
Leslie Knope down.

14:54.429 --> 14:56.063
"She's too real for this ish.

14:56.097 --> 14:59.333
#bossbitch."

14:59.367 --> 15:01.168
"Leslie Knope is stepping up
at these hearings

15:01.219 --> 15:02.300
"and taking a bullet for me.

15:02.303 --> 15:05.372
#sisterfromanothermister,
#bossbitch."

15:05.406 --> 15:07.290
It appears,
whereas "bitch boss"

15:07.325 --> 15:09.343
is clearly an indication
of her frustration,

15:09.377 --> 15:11.511
"boss bitch"
is a term of endearment.

15:11.546 --> 15:12.729
Isn't language fun?

15:12.764 --> 15:14.481
It's like racquetball
for your mouth!

15:14.515 --> 15:15.899
[Sighs]

15:15.917 --> 15:17.617
Did you change your outfit?

15:17.668 --> 15:20.620
I changed five times,
and she hasn't noticed yet.

15:20.655 --> 15:22.539
I can only stall for so long.
What should I do?

15:22.573 --> 15:24.624
Um, I just finished
filling this one out.

15:24.659 --> 15:26.710
I didn't know what to put for
"Name of commercial airline,"

15:26.744 --> 15:28.812
because I do not operate
a commercial airline,

15:28.846 --> 15:29.896
so I just made one up.

15:29.947 --> 15:31.748
What did you name
your imaginary airline?

15:31.783 --> 15:32.799
"Jet Blue Ivy."

15:32.834 --> 15:34.301
I figure Jay-Z
and Beyonce's kid

15:34.335 --> 15:36.987
will own her own airline
eventually.

15:37.021 --> 15:39.139
She's the one.

15:39.173 --> 15:41.842
So, can I have
my permit now? Finally?

15:41.876 --> 15:45.562
Uh, no, there was a mistake,

15:45.596 --> 15:48.031
and we gave the park
to someone else.

15:48.065 --> 15:48.998
What?

15:49.016 --> 15:50.183
Maybe I can drive you around

15:50.218 --> 15:52.319
and we'll pick another one?

15:52.353 --> 15:53.286
Maybe I'll bring
a picnic lunch.

15:53.321 --> 15:54.621
Do you like tamales?

15:54.655 --> 15:56.540
You said that that park
was ours.

15:56.574 --> 15:58.041
You said it a long time ago,

15:58.059 --> 15:59.726
in a British accent.

15:59.761 --> 16:00.977
I probably shouldn't say this,
as a doctor.

16:01.011 --> 16:02.279
It's probably not cool.

16:02.313 --> 16:05.298
But I really hope you all
get West Nile virus.

16:05.349 --> 16:07.768
Nice meeting you, April.

16:07.819 --> 16:09.319
Kind of.
You're weird too.

16:09.353 --> 16:11.088
Thank you.

16:13.591 --> 16:14.591
[Knocks]

16:14.625 --> 16:16.176
We need to talk.

16:16.227 --> 16:18.445
That has never been true.

16:18.496 --> 16:19.963
I think I know
what's happening.

16:19.997 --> 16:22.382
Thinking about how to
divide up your possessions

16:22.433 --> 16:23.850
for when you die,

16:23.901 --> 16:26.403
it's tough, confronting
your own mortality,

16:26.437 --> 16:30.157
and I think it's got you
spinning a little bit.

16:30.191 --> 16:31.558
Am I right?

16:31.592 --> 16:32.893
Wow.

16:32.927 --> 16:35.028
I had not considered that.

16:35.079 --> 16:36.997
Yes, I think that maybe
you are on to something.

16:37.031 --> 16:38.165
Yeah.

16:38.199 --> 16:40.217
Just know that it's
perfectly healthy

16:40.251 --> 16:42.686
to be thinking about--

16:42.720 --> 16:43.937
Oh, you're joking.

16:43.988 --> 16:45.071
Yes, son, I am.

16:45.106 --> 16:46.823
First joke ever.

16:46.857 --> 16:48.291
Don't care for it.

16:48.326 --> 16:50.210
Death does not scare me.

16:50.261 --> 16:52.896
What I am worried about
is spoiling my children.

16:52.930 --> 16:54.614
I don't want 'em to be
the kind of people

16:54.665 --> 16:57.667
who never work,
live off their trust funds,

16:57.702 --> 16:59.669
who buy their wooden furniture.

16:59.704 --> 17:02.305
I will leave my children
$50 apiece

17:02.323 --> 17:03.824
for the cab home
from my funeral

17:03.858 --> 17:06.026
and a steak dinner,
end of discussion.

17:06.077 --> 17:07.077
Okay.

17:07.111 --> 17:08.127
I mean, look, it doesn't matter

17:08.162 --> 17:09.612
how much money
you leave your kids.

17:09.630 --> 17:12.516
What matters is that you teach
them the right values.

17:12.550 --> 17:14.451
But, if something
horrible happens,

17:14.484 --> 17:15.752
and you want your kids
to be left alone

17:15.786 --> 17:16.986
with no safety net,

17:17.003 --> 17:18.622
just so they can learn
some kind of weird lesson,

17:18.656 --> 17:20.891
then, by all means,
leave your fortune

17:20.925 --> 17:24.578
to the wild boar
who gores you to death.

17:24.612 --> 17:28.214
I'd never lose to a boar.

17:28.249 --> 17:29.249
[Dart hits board]

17:34.238 --> 17:36.907
I'm sorry if I can be
little annoying at times,

17:36.941 --> 17:38.842
but one person's annoying

17:38.876 --> 17:41.211
is another person's
inspiring and heroic,

17:41.229 --> 17:44.314
so, you know,
who are we to judge?

17:44.348 --> 17:46.716
And I'm sorry
for writing those things.

17:46.751 --> 17:48.568
Some of those things.

17:48.603 --> 17:51.755
I can't promise
that I won't be inspiring

17:51.789 --> 17:53.473
and heroic in the future.

17:53.508 --> 17:55.809
And I can't promise that I
won't complain about it.

17:55.843 --> 17:57.978
Deal.

17:58.029 --> 17:59.646
I got you an apology present.

17:59.697 --> 18:00.697
Oh!

18:00.731 --> 18:02.098
It is all of
your favorite lipsticks

18:02.116 --> 18:03.099
and nail polishes,

18:03.117 --> 18:04.100
and I got the same ones too.

18:04.118 --> 18:05.235
I printed out a schedule,

18:05.269 --> 18:06.653
so we can wear them
at the same time.

18:06.704 --> 18:08.655
Now, I would like you
to open each one

18:08.706 --> 18:09.746
in front of me, and tell me

18:09.773 --> 18:11.324
how you feel about them
individually.

18:11.375 --> 18:12.909
Let me take a picture.

18:12.944 --> 18:14.244
Are you tweeting this?

18:14.278 --> 18:15.662
Mm-hmm.

18:15.713 --> 18:16.663
What's the hashtag gonna be?

18:16.714 --> 18:17.947
"Boss bitch" or "bitch boss"?

18:17.965 --> 18:19.216
Yeah,
it's "psycho boss."

18:19.250 --> 18:21.673
Eh, I don't hate that.

18:23.354 --> 18:25.702
Benjamin, after thinking
about what you said,

18:25.822 --> 18:26.733
I've decided to leave

18:26.853 --> 18:29.485
each of my children
5% of my fortune.

18:29.605 --> 18:31.823
Wow, 5 whole percent.

18:31.858 --> 18:34.109
So, I guess you are gonna
teach them a lesson.

18:34.143 --> 18:37.379
Oh, my God, that's 5%?

18:37.413 --> 18:39.031
That is a lot of money.

18:39.065 --> 18:40.665
Wait, is this a joke?

18:40.717 --> 18:42.084
It is not a joke.

18:42.118 --> 18:44.052
Not that an accountant
would know the difference.

18:44.087 --> 18:47.222
Also, if something should
happen to Diane and me,

18:47.256 --> 18:49.091
we decided
that the kids should go

18:49.125 --> 18:51.176
to the most important
people in our lives.

18:51.227 --> 18:54.980
Ron, I'm--I'm incredibly
flattered.

18:55.014 --> 18:57.298
Ralph Piatkowski
and his wife Helen.

18:57.316 --> 18:59.735
He's the Maitre D'
at Mulligan's Steakhouse,

18:59.769 --> 19:01.820
and he knows me
better than anyone.

19:01.854 --> 19:03.638
However, if they are not
able to do it,

19:03.656 --> 19:05.991
which seems likely,
as they're in their 90s,

19:06.025 --> 19:08.643
you and Leslie
are choice number two.

19:08.661 --> 19:10.245
I'm honored.

19:10.279 --> 19:11.813
Everyone, take your seats,

19:11.831 --> 19:14.332
so this witch hunt
may proceed as scheduled.

19:14.367 --> 19:16.418
Speaking of, uh,
where are the witches?

19:16.452 --> 19:17.869
They're right here!

19:17.920 --> 19:20.455
Well, we're not witches.
That's sexist and offensive.

19:20.489 --> 19:21.656
But we're right here,

19:21.674 --> 19:23.341
and we are not gonna
sit in this room

19:23.376 --> 19:25.177
and let you drag our names
through the mud

19:25.211 --> 19:27.179
just to score some
cheap political points.

19:27.213 --> 19:29.097
How dare you demean the value

19:29.132 --> 19:31.049
of the political points
I'm scoring?

19:31.100 --> 19:32.467
We have had enough.

19:32.501 --> 19:34.770
I am going back to work so I can
do some good for this town,

19:34.804 --> 19:36.772
and my friend Donna
is coming with me.

19:36.806 --> 19:38.557
Hmm.
I prefer "El Diablo."

19:38.608 --> 19:40.675
Uh, this is not over,
Ms. Knope!

19:40.693 --> 19:43.228
Donna, quit punishing me!

19:43.279 --> 19:45.147
- I miss you.
- Uh-uh!

19:45.181 --> 19:47.182
Bridge burned, Typhoon.

19:47.200 --> 19:50.202
Or should I say, "Norman"?
Uh-huh.

19:50.236 --> 19:52.353
Okay, I'm just gonna man up,

19:52.371 --> 19:53.855
tell her how I feel,

19:53.873 --> 19:55.073
and hope she feels
the same way about me,

19:55.124 --> 19:56.208
and that's that.

19:56.242 --> 19:57.325
If she doesn't,
no big deal. It's done.

19:57.359 --> 19:58.460
I'm an adult.
Let's do it.

19:58.494 --> 20:00.212
Great.

20:00.246 --> 20:02.247
Nope, I can't do it.
New plan.

20:02.298 --> 20:03.381
Tell her all the screw-ups
were your fault.

20:03.416 --> 20:04.800
I'll tell her I had to
cover for you,

20:04.834 --> 20:05.801
because you are so dumb.

20:05.835 --> 20:08.136
Nadia!

20:08.171 --> 20:10.755
We're very sorry for everything
you went through today.

20:10.807 --> 20:13.975
I have reserved the park
for your event.

20:14.010 --> 20:17.813
Now, April has something
she'd like to admit.

20:17.847 --> 20:19.931
Tom wants me to tell you that
all the screw-ups were my fault,

20:19.982 --> 20:22.050
but really, he kept messing up
so that you would

20:22.068 --> 20:23.268
stay in Pawnee
as long as possible

20:23.319 --> 20:25.103
because he is super into you.

20:25.154 --> 20:28.056
Okay.

20:28.074 --> 20:29.441
Several questions.

20:29.492 --> 20:31.660
- Is any part of him British?
- No.

20:31.694 --> 20:33.411
So, that was just weird,
panicky dude behavior?

20:33.446 --> 20:34.496
- Yeah.
- Okay.

20:34.530 --> 20:35.690
I'm just trying to figure out

20:35.698 --> 20:38.266
if acting that insane
is, like, romantic,

20:38.284 --> 20:39.818
or totally scary.

20:39.869 --> 20:42.454
I'll go with romantic.

20:42.488 --> 20:43.889
He is kind of cute.

20:43.923 --> 20:45.457
What's his deal?

20:45.491 --> 20:47.375
He's sweet, he's cool,

20:47.410 --> 20:48.793
and you're, like,
way out of his league,

20:48.828 --> 20:51.946
so there's literally
no risk for you at all here.

20:51.964 --> 20:52.947
Okay.

20:52.965 --> 20:54.366
Well, I am going
to Rwanda in, like,

20:54.400 --> 20:56.284
two weeks for my job,
so, what the hell?

20:56.302 --> 20:57.419
Cool.

20:57.453 --> 20:58.470
So, you want to go out with me?

20:58.504 --> 20:59.971
Yes, please.

21:00.006 --> 21:02.974
Okay. Bye.

21:03.009 --> 21:05.627
Okay, you owe me,
like, 1,000 favors.

21:05.645 --> 21:07.312
See ya.

21:07.641 --> 21:15.115
